1
00:02:36,491 --> 00:02:37,546
<i>So, where are you?

2
00:02:37,570 --> 00:02:39,724
<i>You're in.. some motel room..</i>

3
00:02:39,749 --> 00:02:42,793
<i>You just.. You just wake up, and
you're in.. in a motel room.

4
00:02:42,930 --> 00:02:44,333
<i>There's the key.

5
00:02:44,357 --> 00:02:47,714
<i>It feels like maybe it's just the
first time you've been there but...</i>

6
00:02:47,739 --> 00:02:50,948
<i>perhaps.. you've been there for a week..

7
00:02:51,209 --> 00:02:52,751
<i>three months..

8
00:02:52,877 --> 00:02:55,734
<i>It's.. It's kinda hard to say.
I.. I don't know.</i>

9
00:02:56,012 --> 00:02:58,219
<i>It's just.. an anonymous room.</i>

10
00:02:58,456 --> 00:03:00,809
<i>Nothing in the drawers.
But you look anyway.

11
00:03:00,867 --> 00:03:06,493
<i>Nothing except the Gideon Bible,
which I of course, read religiously.

12
00:03:07,907 --> 00:03:12,293
<i>You know who you are,
and you know kind of all about yourself.

13
00:03:12,318 --> 00:03:17,137
<i>But just for day-to-day stuff,
notes are really useful.

14
00:03:17,855 --> 00:03:20,672
<i>Sammy Jankis had the same problem...

15
00:03:20,697 --> 00:03:22,698
<i>but he.. he really had no system.

16
00:03:22,723 --> 00:03:25,145
<i>He wrote himself
a ridiculous amount of notes...

17
00:03:25,170 --> 00:03:27,254
<i>but he'd get them all mixed up.

18
00:03:27,636 --> 00:03:31,746
<i>You really do need a system
if you're gonna make it work.

19
00:03:32,397 --> 00:03:35,770
<i>You kind of learn
to trust your own handwriting.

20
00:03:35,795 --> 00:03:39,735
<i>That becomes an important part of your life.
You write yourself notes...

21
00:03:39,760 --> 00:03:42,612
<i>and where you put your notes...
That also becomes really important.

22
00:03:42,989 --> 00:03:45,227
<i>You need like, a jacket that's got
like, six pockets in it.

23
00:03:45,252 --> 00:03:47,313
<i>Particular pockets for particular things.

24
00:03:47,338 --> 00:03:51,473
<i>You just kind of learn to know
where things go and how the system works.

25
00:03:51,533 --> 00:03:55,411
<i>And you have to be wary of other people writing
stuff for you that is not gonna make sense...

26
00:03:55,436 --> 00:03:56,591
<i>or is gonna lead you astray.

27
00:03:56,615 --> 00:04:00,816
<i>I mean.. I.. I don't know. I guess people try and take
advantage of somebody with this condition.

28
00:04:02,083 --> 00:04:07,160
<i>If you have a piece
of information which is vital...

29
00:04:07,185 --> 00:04:10,520
<i>writing on your body instead of
on a piece of paper can be the answer.

30
00:04:10,640 --> 00:04:13,518
<i>It's just a permanent way of keeping a note.

31
00:04:20,428 --> 00:04:21,928
Who is this?

32
00:04:22,808 --> 00:04:24,726
You said we talked before.
I don't remember that.

33
00:04:25,526 --> 00:04:27,026
Yeah, but it's not amnesia.

34
00:04:27,403 --> 00:04:29,905
I remember everything up until my injury.
I just can't make new memories.

35
00:04:29,930 --> 00:04:32,692
So I can't remember talking to you.
What did we talk about?

36
00:04:32,722 --> 00:04:34,278
Oh, Sammy Jankis.

37
00:04:34,303 --> 00:04:36,685
I guess I tell people about Sammy
to help them understand.

38
00:04:36,861 --> 00:04:39,085
Sammy's story helps me
understand my own situation.

39
00:04:39,833 --> 00:04:42,389
Sammy wrote himself endless
amounts of notes...

40
00:04:43,971 --> 00:04:45,471
But he got mixed up.

41
00:04:45,617 --> 00:04:48,192
I have a more graceful
solution to the memory problem.

42
00:04:51,565 --> 00:04:53,357
I'm disciplined and organized.

43
00:04:54,283 --> 00:04:57,002
I use habit and routine
to make my life possible.

44
00:04:57,874 --> 00:05:00,333
Sammy had no drive,
no reason to make it work.

45
00:05:01,844 --> 00:05:03,682
Me?
Yeah...

46
00:05:04,852 --> 00:05:06,352
I got a reason.

47
00:05:08,107 --> 00:05:11,629
I met Sammy through work;
Insurance - I was an investigator.

48
00:05:11,865 --> 00:05:14,325
I'd investigate the claims
to see which ones were phony.

49
00:05:14,544 --> 00:05:16,547
I had to see through people's bullshit.

50
00:05:17,029 --> 00:05:19,405
It was useful experience,
'cause now it's my life.

51
00:05:20,117 --> 00:05:22,743
But when I meet someone,
I don't know if I've met them before.

52
00:05:23,102 --> 00:05:25,838
I have to just look in their eyes
and try and figure them out.

53
00:05:25,960 --> 00:05:29,123
<i>My job taught me the best way to find out
what someone knew was just let them talk.</i>

54
00:05:29,148 --> 00:05:31,383
<i>And watch the eyes. And the body language..</i>

55
00:05:31,578 --> 00:05:33,589
<i>If someone scratches their
nose while they're talking,</i>

56
00:05:33,614 --> 00:05:35,367
<i>experts will tell you
it means they're lying.</i>

57
00:05:35,633 --> 00:05:38,778
<i>It really means they're nervous.
People get nervous for all sorts of reasons.</i>

58
00:05:38,945 --> 00:05:40,304
<i>It's all about context.</i>

59
00:05:40,328 --> 00:05:41,828
Yeah, I was good.

60
00:05:42,148 --> 00:05:44,681
Sammy was my first real challenge.

61
00:05:47,031 --> 00:05:49,336
I'd just become an investigator
when I came across Sammy.

62
00:05:49,695 --> 00:05:53,152
Mr. Samuel R. Jankis. Strangest case ever.

63
00:05:53,297 --> 00:05:56,188
You know, the guy's a 58-year-old
semi-retired accountant.

64
00:05:56,213 --> 00:05:58,940
He and his wife had been in this car accident.
Nothing too serious.

65
00:05:59,047 --> 00:06:01,865
<i>But he's acting funny.
He can't get a handle on what's going on.</i>

66
00:06:03,461 --> 00:06:07,443
<i>The doctors find some possible damage
to the hippocampus. Nothing conclusive.</i>

67
00:06:07,944 --> 00:06:10,685
<i>But Sammy can't remember
anything for more than a couple of minutes.</i>

68
00:06:11,117 --> 00:06:13,741
<i>Can't work, can't do shit.
The medical bills pile up.</i>

69
00:06:13,766 --> 00:06:16,492
<i>His wife calls the insurance company,
and I get sent in.</i>

70
00:06:17,281 --> 00:06:21,380
<i>Now, this is my first big claims investigation,
so I really check into it.</i>

71
00:06:22,008 --> 00:06:24,436
<i>Sammy can think just fine.</i>

72
00:06:24,650 --> 00:06:26,485
<i>But he can't make any new memories.</i>

73
00:06:26,992 --> 00:06:28,881
<i>He could only remember things
for a couple of minutes.</i>

74
00:06:29,404 --> 00:06:30,889
- This is Mr. Shelby.
<i>- He'd watch TV...

75
00:06:30,913 --> 00:06:33,529
<i>but anything longer than
a couple of minutes was too confusing.</i>

76
00:06:33,554 --> 00:06:35,054
<i>He couldn't remember how it began.</i>

77
00:06:35,589 --> 00:06:37,345
<i>He liked commercials. They were short.</i>

78
00:06:37,672 --> 00:06:39,695
Sammy. It's time for my shot.

79
00:06:39,774 --> 00:06:41,274
<i>The crazy part was...</i>

80
00:06:41,805 --> 00:06:45,254
<i>that this guy, who couldn't even follow the
plot of Green Acres anymore...</i>

81
00:06:45,788 --> 00:06:47,754
<i>could do the most complicated things...</i>

82
00:06:48,883 --> 00:06:51,020
<i>as long as he learned them
before the accident...</i>

83
00:06:53,125 --> 00:06:55,048
<i>and as long as he kept his mind
on what he was doing.</i>

84
00:06:55,155 --> 00:06:56,655
Be gentle.

85
00:06:56,711 --> 00:07:01,674
<i>Now, the doctors assure me there's a real condition
called "Anterograde Memory Loss"...</i>

86
00:07:01,699 --> 00:07:03,531
<i>or "Short-term memory loss".</i>

87
00:07:03,556 --> 00:07:05,341
<i>It's rare, but legit.</i>

88
00:07:07,141 --> 00:07:08,641
<i>But every time I see him...</i>

89
00:07:10,188 --> 00:07:11,819
<i>I catch this look...</i>

90
00:07:11,844 --> 00:07:15,097
<i>this.. slight look of recognition.</i>

91
00:07:16,281 --> 00:07:18,084
<i>But he says he can't remember me at all.</i>

92
00:07:18,109 --> 00:07:20,758
Sammy, it's okay. I got it. I got it.

93
00:07:21,094 --> 00:07:23,516
- Hi, Mr. Shelby.
- Hi, Mrs. Jankis.

94
00:07:23,727 --> 00:07:27,781
<i>Now, I can read people, and
I'm thinking: Bad actor.</i>

95
00:07:28,461 --> 00:07:30,618
So now I'm suspicious, and I order more tests.

96
00:07:31,746 --> 00:07:33,601
Sammy couldn't pick up any new skills at all.

97
00:07:34,707 --> 00:07:36,522
But I find something in my research:

98
00:07:36,861 --> 00:07:38,406
"Conditioning".

99
00:07:38,430 --> 00:07:40,935
Sammy should still be able to learn
through repetition.

100
00:07:41,547 --> 00:07:44,686
It's how you learn stuff like riding a bike.
You just get better through practice.

101
00:07:44,992 --> 00:07:47,381
It's a completely different part of the brain
from the short-term memory.

102
00:07:47,586 --> 00:07:50,516
So I had the doctors test
Sammy's response to conditioning.

103
00:07:50,578 --> 00:07:52,632
Just pick up any three objects.

104
00:07:53,297 --> 00:07:54,797
That's a test?

105
00:07:55,531 --> 00:07:57,863
Where were you guys when I did my CPA?

106
00:07:58,913 --> 00:08:00,413
Sorry.

107
00:08:01,242 --> 00:08:02,742
Ta-da!

108
00:08:03,809 --> 00:08:06,023
Ow! What the fuck?

109
00:08:06,048 --> 00:08:09,141
- It's a test, Sammy.
- Well, test this, you fucking quack!

110
00:08:10,555 --> 00:08:12,055
<i>Some of the objects were electrified.</i>

111
00:08:12,584 --> 00:08:15,054
<i>They'd give him a small shock.
They kept repeating the test...</i>

112
00:08:15,180 --> 00:08:16,789
always with the same objects electrified.

113
00:08:17,094 --> 00:08:20,631
The point was to see if Sammy could learn
to avoid the electrified objects...

114
00:08:20,656 --> 00:08:22,711
not by memory, but by instinct.

115
00:08:24,344 --> 00:08:25,844
They kept testing Sammy for months...

116
00:08:26,672 --> 00:08:28,979
Always with the same objects
carrying the electrical charge.

117
00:08:30,559 --> 00:08:31,890
Ow! What the fuck?

118
00:08:31,914 --> 00:08:34,553
- It's a test, Sammy.
- Test this, you fucking quack!

119
00:08:34,797 --> 00:08:36,661
Even with total short-term memory loss...

120
00:08:36,686 --> 00:08:40,216
<i>Sammy should have learned to instinctively stop
picking up the wrong objects.</i>

121
00:08:40,348 --> 00:08:44,059
<i>All the previous cases responded to conditioning.
Sammy didn't respond at all.</i>

122
00:08:44,336 --> 00:08:48,070
<i>It was enough to suggest that his condition
was psychological, not physical.</i>

123
00:08:48,266 --> 00:08:51,164
We turned down his claim on the grounds
that he wasn't covered for mental illness.

124
00:08:52,508 --> 00:08:54,695
His wife got stuck with the bills,
and I got a big promotion.

125
00:08:57,258 --> 00:09:00,147
Conditioning didn't work for Sammy.
-So he became helpless.

126
00:09:00,641 --> 00:09:02,938
But it works for me.

127
00:09:02,963 --> 00:09:04,962
I live the way Sammy couldn't.

128
00:09:05,024 --> 00:09:07,429
Habit and routine make my life possible.

129
00:09:07,668 --> 00:09:09,168
Conditioning.

130
00:09:09,384 --> 00:09:10,884
Acting on instinct.

131
00:09:11,734 --> 00:09:14,585
Sammy's wife was crippled
by the cost of supporting him.

132
00:09:15,195 --> 00:09:16,841
And fighting the company's decision...

133
00:09:18,883 --> 00:09:20,476
But it wasn't the money that got to her.

134
00:09:21,406 --> 00:09:24,242
<i>- I never said that Sammy was faking.</i>
- Listen. I have an idea.

135
00:09:24,430 --> 00:09:25,930
Sammy, I have an idea.

136
00:09:25,999 --> 00:09:28,471
<i>Just that his problem was mental, not physical.</i>

137
00:09:28,496 --> 00:09:32,033
I want you to have a pen in your pocket, okay?
You're gonna have a pen in your pocket.

138
00:09:32,058 --> 00:09:34,422
<i>- But she couldn't understand.</i>
And you're gonna have a pad. Like that.

139
00:09:34,447 --> 00:09:36,744
...in your pocket. - I did something wrong?
- You did something wrong!

140
00:09:36,769 --> 00:09:40,185
Now, we're gonna deal with it. We'll figure out..
We're gonna try a little harder.

141
00:09:40,210 --> 00:09:42,153
<i>She looks into his eyes
and sees the same person,</i>

142
00:09:42,178 --> 00:09:45,506
<i>and if it's not a physical problem,
he should just.. snap out of it.</i>

143
00:09:45,531 --> 00:09:48,191
- Ellen called!
- Ellen called?

144
00:09:48,414 --> 00:09:51,422
- Ellen can't come today! Ellen can't come!
- Okay. I'm sorry!

145
00:09:51,461 --> 00:09:55,216
- I'm sorry. I'm trying. I'm sorry.
- Try harder!

146
00:09:58,832 --> 00:10:03,086
So good old Leonard Shelby from the insurance
company gives her the seed of doubt...

147
00:10:03,604 --> 00:10:05,108
just like he gave it to the doctors.

148
00:10:06,281 --> 00:10:08,811
But I never said that he was faking.
I never said that.

149
00:10:14,046 --> 00:10:17,496
Well, what Mrs. Jankis didn't understand was
that you can't bully someone into remembering.

150
00:10:18,029 --> 00:10:20,086
The more pressure you're under,
the harder it gets.

151
00:10:22,703 --> 00:10:26,344
Well, then call m.. call me back?

152
00:11:01,336 --> 00:11:02,836
Who is this?

153
00:11:05,156 --> 00:11:06,499
Yeah.

154
00:11:06,523 --> 00:11:08,023
Uh-huh.

155
00:11:09,445 --> 00:11:12,797
Well, sir, that'd certainly be in keeping
with some of my own discoveries.

156
00:11:13,313 --> 00:11:16,417
I was hoping for a little more on the drugs angle.
Can you hang on a sec?

157
00:11:25,211 --> 00:11:28,586
The police report mentioned
the drugs found in the car outside my house.

158
00:11:28,617 --> 00:11:30,438
The car was stolen,
but his prints were all over it.

159
00:11:31,008 --> 00:11:33,020
I got friends in the department.
They gave me a copy of it.

160
00:11:33,291 --> 00:11:35,727
I dealt with the police a lot
in my insurance job.

161
00:11:35,752 --> 00:11:39,786
In my condition, it's really tough.
I can't keep it all in mind at once.

162
00:11:40,196 --> 00:11:43,354
I have to summarize the different sections.
And there's pages missing.

163
00:11:43,492 --> 00:11:44,992
I guess I've been trying to log them all.

164
00:11:45,555 --> 00:11:47,162
I don't know why these are crossed out.

165
00:11:47,907 --> 00:11:49,665
But they weren't even looking for John G.

166
00:11:49,891 --> 00:11:52,236
The stuff they found in the car just fit in with
what they believed had happened

167
00:11:52,261 --> 00:11:53,761
so they didn't chase any of it up.

168
00:11:56,539 --> 00:11:59,461
There's something about the drugs stashed
in the car that doesn't ring true for me.

169
00:12:00,172 --> 00:12:01,938
Because the police claim
the guy was an addict

170
00:12:01,969 --> 00:12:03,996
needing money to score,
which I think is bullshit

171
00:12:04,021 --> 00:12:07,617
'cause he's not gonna go breaking into places
while he's still got a stash that big.

172
00:12:08,438 --> 00:12:11,250
Well, I think John G. Left it there.
Or planted it there.

173
00:12:13,047 --> 00:12:14,547
How do you know that?

174
00:12:16,633 --> 00:12:18,199
Oh, shit, that's true. It fits.

175
00:12:19,156 --> 00:12:20,656
So he's a dealer.

176
00:12:21,777 --> 00:12:23,277
Hang on a sec.

177
00:12:33,827 --> 00:12:35,506
Now we're getting somewhere.

178
00:12:37,239 --> 00:12:39,007
I can't blame the cops
for not taking me seriously;

179
00:12:39,032 --> 00:12:41,261
this is a difficult condition
for people to understand.

180
00:12:41,408 --> 00:12:44,367
I mean, look at Sammy Jankis.
His own wife couldn't deal with it...

181
00:12:44,885 --> 00:12:47,338
I told you about how she tried
to get him to snap out of it.

182
00:12:47,363 --> 00:12:50,496
Eventually she came to see me at the office.
I found out all kinds of shit.

183
00:12:51,156 --> 00:12:53,866
<i>She told me about life with
Sammy - how she treated him.</i>

184
00:12:53,891 --> 00:12:55,216
Thank you for seeing me.

185
00:12:55,240 --> 00:12:58,058
You know, it got to the point where she'd get Sammy
to hide food all around the house,

186
00:12:58,083 --> 00:12:59,718
and then she'd stop feeding him
to see if his hunger

187
00:12:59,743 --> 00:13:01,417
would make him remember
where he'd hidden the food.

188
00:13:04,336 --> 00:13:06,682
<i>She wasn't a cruel person.
She just wanted old Sammy back.</i>

189
00:13:06,922 --> 00:13:10,474
Mr. Shelby. You know all about Sammy
and you've decided that he's faking.

190
00:13:10,591 --> 00:13:13,524
Mrs. Jankis, the company's position
isn't that Sammy is faking anything,

191
00:13:13,549 --> 00:13:15,463
just that his condition can't be shown to be ph...

192
00:13:15,488 --> 00:13:18,482
I just want to know what your honest opinion about Sammy is.

193
00:13:18,507 --> 00:13:22,142
Ah... We shouldn't even be talking like this
while the case is still open to appeal.

194
00:13:22,167 --> 00:13:24,011
I'm not appealing the decision.

195
00:13:24,259 --> 00:13:25,417
Then why are you here?

196
00:13:25,442 --> 00:13:27,859
Try to understand.
When I look at Sammy...

197
00:13:27,977 --> 00:13:29,477
I don't see some...

198
00:13:30,128 --> 00:13:31,554
Vegetable.

199
00:13:31,578 --> 00:13:33,144
I see my same old Sammy.

200
00:13:35,855 --> 00:13:39,197
What do you think that's like for me
to suspect that he might be imagining

201
00:13:39,222 --> 00:13:41,942
this whole problem, and that if I
just could say the right thing,

202
00:13:41,967 --> 00:13:44,803
he'd snap out of it and go back to being normal?

203
00:13:46,820 --> 00:13:48,320
If I...

204
00:13:50,930 --> 00:13:54,461
If I knew that my
old Sammy were truly gone,

205
00:13:54,486 --> 00:13:58,310
then I could say good-bye
and start loving this new Sammy.

206
00:14:00,972 --> 00:14:03,615
As long as I have doubt, I can't
say good-bye and move on.

207
00:14:04,039 --> 00:14:05,437
What do you want from me?

208
00:14:05,461 --> 00:14:09,097
I want you to forget the company
you work for for 30 seconds and...

209
00:14:09,122 --> 00:14:12,828
tell me if you really believe
that Sammy's faking his condition?

210
00:14:13,898 --> 00:14:15,398
I need to know...

211
00:14:15,999 --> 00:14:17,517
what you honestly believe.

212
00:14:22,977 --> 00:14:26,273
I believe that Sammy should be physically
capable of making new memories.

213
00:14:34,867 --> 00:14:36,367
Thank you.

214
00:14:38,263 --> 00:14:41,172
I thought I helped her.
I thought she just needed some kind of answer.

215
00:14:41,578 --> 00:14:43,205
I didn't think it was important
what the answer was...

216
00:14:43,973 --> 00:14:45,379
Just that she had one to believe.

217
00:14:45,404 --> 00:14:46,904
<i>"FACT 5:
DRUGDEALER"</i>

218
00:14:53,285 --> 00:14:55,582
No! She shouldn't have
given me that responsibility.

219
00:14:56,317 --> 00:14:58,417
I'm a claims investigator, not a doctor...

220
00:15:00,016 --> 00:15:02,234
Yeah, I guess.

221
00:15:02,506 --> 00:15:04,176
But I've got all sorts of other considerations.

222
00:15:05,674 --> 00:15:07,716
Legal responsibility, large financ...

223
00:15:08,629 --> 00:15:11,322
<i>"NEVER ANSWER THE PHONE"</i>

224
00:15:13,016 --> 00:15:14,516
